---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import BrandBranchesGrid from '../../components/BrandBranchesGrid.astro';
import { MAIN_PHONE, MAIN_PHONE_TEL } from '../../data/branches';

const title = "Dacor Refrigerator Repair | Southern California | Modernist Column";
const description = "Dacor refrigerator repair across Southern California — Modernist Column, French Door, FreshZone drawers. California-founded (1965), Samsung-owned since 2016. $89 diagnostic. (424) 325-0520.";
const canonical = "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/dacor-refrigerator-repair/";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Is Dacor a California company or is it Korean now?",
    a: "Both, actually — and the California side is the part most homeowners don't realize. Dacor was founded in Pasadena in 1965 by Stanley M. Joseph as Distinctive Appliances Corporation, and ran as a family-owned California company for three generations (Joseph's sons Michael and Anthony took over in the second generation) until Samsung Electronics acquired the business in August 2016 for about $150 million. What's less obvious: Dacor is still headquartered in Southern California. The US operations are now in Diamond Bar, a roughly 30-mile drive east of our Los Angeles branch. Product engineering, sales, and leadership sit there; Samsung provides the refrigeration platform (shared compressor architecture with Samsung's premium Bespoke line) and international distribution infrastructure. Practically, for service: Dacor's California roots mean we've been opening these refrigerators since before the Samsung deal, and the Samsung-era parts chain is notably strong in LA because the Diamond Bar operation is local."
  },
  {
    q: "How does Samsung ownership affect parts availability and repair cost?",
    a: "Positively, on balance. Before 2016, Dacor refrigerators ran a smaller independent parts chain — factory-exact items could take 5–10 business days to LA, and some service-critical components went on backorder for weeks. Since the Samsung acquisition, Dacor's current-generation refrigerators share significant compressor and sealed-system platform architecture with Samsung's premium Bespoke and Family Hub refrigerator lines. That means the parts our techs need are often stocked in the same regional distribution centers Samsung uses for its full lineup, which shortens service lead times. On the cost side, Samsung-shared platforms mean parts pricing is more competitive than pre-2016 boutique-Dacor parts. The trade-off: some Dacor enthusiasts feel the brand has lost some of its independent-California character. From a pure service perspective though, the Samsung-era Dacor refrigerator is easier to repair and parts-source than the pre-2016 units."
  },
  {
    q: "Our architect specified a Dacor Modernist Column DRR30980 — how does it compare to Sub-Zero or Thermador columns for service?",
    a: "The Modernist Column is Dacor's direct answer to Sub-Zero's 648PRO and Thermador's Freedom Collection columns. On paper, specs are competitive: 30-inch and 36-inch widths, integrated panel-ready design, three-zone cooling with dedicated FreshZone compartment, 21.6 cu ft on the 36. Service-side, a few honest notes. Build quality is genuinely close to Sub-Zero — the gauge steel, the door-closer mechanics, the compressor isolation mounting. Where the Modernist Column has a service advantage: the Samsung-shared Digital Inverter compressor platform has a wider parts-sourcing network than Sub-Zero's proprietary variable-speed compressor. Where Sub-Zero wins: legacy parts availability on 10-plus-year-old units (Sub-Zero supports very old units well; Dacor's pre-2016 independent parts chain didn't, though the Samsung era has improved forward-looking availability). For a new install, our techs rate Modernist Column a strong value pick at 10–20% below equivalent Sub-Zero pricing with comparable long-term repair economics."
  },
  {
    q: "What is FreshZone and how is it different from a regular produce drawer?",
    a: "FreshZone is Dacor's climate-controlled full-width drawer that sits between the fresh-food compartment and the freezer. It holds a temperature range from roughly 29°F (chill) through 41°F (produce) with humidity control, and on Modernist Column and Contemporary French Door SKUs it has its own sensor and airflow management separate from the main fresh-food box. Service implication: FreshZone can surface symptoms the main compartment never sees. A homeowner who reports \"produce in the bottom drawer is freezing\" or \"meats stored there aren't holding temperature\" is usually describing a FreshZone issue, not a whole-fridge issue. Diagnosis order on our service calls: verify the mode the drawer is set to (chill vs. produce vs. pantry), read the FreshZone zone sensor through the Dacor diagnostic interface, check the airflow baffle for frost blockage, and inspect the drain routing if moisture is accumulating in the drawer pan. Sensor replacement $180–$340; baffle defrost + verify $160–$260."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you service older pre-Samsung Dacor refrigerators — the 2005–2015 units?",
    a: "Yes, regularly. The pre-Samsung Dacor refrigerators (the Preference series, early Contemporary models, first-gen Modernist prototypes) are still in service across LA, especially in houses built in 2008–2014 when Dacor was a favored spec for California custom builders. Service on those older units is a different conversation than current-gen: the independent parts chain Dacor ran pre-2016 supplied some platform-specific boards and sensors that went end-of-production without Samsung-era equivalents. Our techs have sourcing relationships for the older platforms, but on a 15-plus-year-old pre-Samsung Dacor with a control-board fault, we'll tell you straight whether the repair pencils against current replacement cost. The compressor and sealed-system side on pre-Samsung units is often still serviceable — those components had longer parts lifecycles than the electronics. If the fault is refrigeration-side (compressor, evap, condenser, defrost), older Dacor repair usually makes sense; if it's a board fault on a discontinued architecture, we have the honest conversation first."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I know if my Dacor is a Modernist, Contemporary, or the older Preference series?",
    a: "The design language tells you quickly. Modernist Column (2017-onwards): flush-front integrated panel-ready, 30-inch or 36-inch column, plinth sits in line with cabinetry, no exposed hinges. Contemporary French Door (2015-onwards, refreshed multiple times): stainless or Bordeaux finishes, exposed hinges, French Door upper with drawer-style freezer lower, Dacor \"Dual-Flash\" handles on newer units. Preference (pre-2016): older architecture, different handle design, mostly stainless, more traditional proportions. Model number on the interior wall confirms: DRR prefix for Modernist Refrigerator columns, DRZ and DRD for Contemporary French Door variants, EF24 for built-in undercounter, DWR for wine columns. If you're unsure, snap a photo of the model plate (usually on the left interior wall just inside the door) and our dispatcher can identify the platform before the truck rolls."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you service Dacor built-in wine columns — they're paired with refrigerators in a lot of LA kitchens?",
    a: "Yes. Dacor's DWR series wine columns are often spec'd next to the Modernist Column refrigerator in Beverly Hills, Hollywood Hills, and Westside built-for-entertaining kitchens. Service profile is adjacent to the refrigerator column: three-zone temperature control, proprietary door-hinge system, panel-ready fronts. Common failures: perimeter gasket compression loss on the tall wine door (similar to refrigerator columns), evaporator fan bearing, and zone-temperature drift (sensor-driven, diagnosable through the Dacor diagnostic interface). Wine-specific context on our <a href='/services/wine-cooler-repair/'>wine cooler repair</a> page. Household with both a Modernist Column and a DWR wine column, we run both on the same service visit — the brand-family, the diagnostic tools, and the parts channels are identical."
  },
  {
    q: "What does Dacor refrigerator repair typically cost in LA?",
    a: "Residential diagnostic is $89, waived when you authorize the repair. Common Dacor refrigerator bands our techs quote: door gasket (Contemporary French Door) $220–$400; door gasket (Modernist Column) $280–$460 (panel-weight considerations); FreshZone sensor or baffle service $180–$360; condenser fan motor $280–$480; evaporator fan $260–$440; defrost heater and thermostat $300–$520; main control board $480–$780; Samsung-shared Digital Inverter compressor replacement $1,000–$1,800 (varies by SKU and refrigerant); ice-maker fill valve + descaling on hard-water households $280–$440; integrated-panel hinge re-shim $240–$420; DWR wine column evaporator service $380–$580. Pre-2016 Preference-series units occasionally require higher parts cost on legacy platform components — we quote the specific SKU before authorization so the older-unit premium is transparent."
  },
  {
    q: "Dacor 10-year warranty on Modernist Column compressors — does that cover the repair labor too?",
    a: "Partial yes, partial no — and it's a question we field weekly. Dacor's current Modernist Column warranty is industry-leading on paper: 2 years full parts and labor, 10 years on the sealed refrigeration system (compressor, evaporator, condenser — parts only), 12 years on the compressor specifically (parts only). What the 10-year and 12-year coverage does NOT include is labor — that shifts to the homeowner after year 2. For an out-of-labor-warranty compressor replacement where Dacor supplies the part under sealed-system coverage, our labor cost on the install is the service quote (typically $600–$1,100 labor alone for a Modernist Column compressor swap, depending on SKU). We work directly with the Dacor warranty claim process if the part is covered; our invoice itemizes the labor-only charge against the factory-supplied part. Bring any factory warranty documentation to the first service visit and our dispatcher will navigate the coverage check with you."
  },
  {
    q: "Are your technicians Dacor-certified — and does that matter for a repair?",
    a: "We service Dacor as a regular part of our luxury brand scope. Our techs are trained on Dacor platforms — pre-Samsung Preference, current Modernist Column, and Contemporary French Door — and we run the Dacor diagnostic interface on service calls. Factory-certified Dacor service providers in the US are coordinated through a handful of authorized networks, primarily for first-year factory warranty work. For units still under factory warranty, call Dacor customer care to route to the factory-authorized service network. For out-of-warranty service, our team handles the repair directly with genuine Dacor parts sourced through the Samsung-era aftermarket channel. Where certification matters most is during the first 24 months when Dacor covers labor; after that, independent LA service with proper Dacor training (ours) is comparable in quality to the factory network and typically more responsive on scheduling."
  }
];

const schemaJsons = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "LocalBusiness",
    "@id": canonical + "#business",
    "name": "Same Day Appliance Repair — Dacor Refrigerator Service",
    "image": "https://samedayappliance.repair/images/same-day-appliance-repair.png",
    "url": canonical,
    "telephone": MAIN_PHONE_TEL,
    "priceRange": "$$$$",
    "areaServed": [
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Los Angeles County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Orange County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Ventura County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "San Bernardino County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Riverside County" }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Service",
    "serviceType": "Dacor Refrigerator Repair",
    "provider": { "@id": canonical + "#business" },
    "areaServed": [
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Los Angeles County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Orange County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Ventura County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "San Bernardino County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Riverside County" }
    ],
    "description": "Dacor refrigerator repair across Los Angeles — Modernist Column built-ins (DRR30980, DRR36980), Contemporary French Door, FreshZone climate-controlled drawer, DWR wine columns, Samsung-shared Digital Inverter compressor service. California-founded (1965), Samsung-owned since 2016. $89 residential diagnostic waived with repair.",
    "offers": {
      "@type": "Offer",
      "priceSpecification": {
        "@type": "PriceSpecification",
        "price": "89.00",
        "priceCurrency": "USD",
        "description": "Residential diagnostic fee, waived with repair"
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": f.q,
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": f.a }
    }))
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://samedayappliance.repair/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Brands", "item": "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Dacor", "item": "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/dacor/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 4, "name": "Dacor Refrigerator Repair", "item": canonical }
    ]
  }
];
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>
  <Fragment slot="head-scripts">
    {schemaJsons.map((schema) => (
      <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
    ))}
  </Fragment>

  <div class="call-banner">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span>Dacor Modernist Column down? Same-day service across LA:</span>
      <a href={`tel:${MAIN_PHONE_TEL}`} class="phone-lg">{MAIN_PHONE}</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="hero"><div class="wrap">
          <div class="crumb"><a href="/">Home</a> › <a href="/brands/">Brands</a> › <a href="/brands/dacor/">Dacor</a> › Refrigerator Repair</div>
          <h1>Dacor Refrigerator Repair</h1>
          <p class="lede">
            Dacor is the Pasadena-founded luxury refrigeration brand most LA homeowners don't realize started just
            down the freeway — 60 years of California design, now Samsung-backed with the HQ still in Diamond Bar.
            Our techs service the full Dacor lineup: Modernist Column built-ins (DRR30980, DRR36980), Contemporary
            French Door, FreshZone climate drawers, DWR wine columns, and pre-2016 Preference-series units still
            running in custom-build kitchens across Beverly Hills, Pacific Palisades, Hollywood Hills, and the
            Westside. Same-day dispatch, $89 residential diagnostic waived with the repair.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-cta">
            <a href={`tel:${MAIN_PHONE_TEL}`} class="btn btn-primary">Call {MAIN_PHONE}</a>
            <a href="#book" class="btn btn-ghost">Request a Visit</a>
          </div>
          <ul class="hero-facts">
            <li><b>California-founded 1965</b> — Pasadena-born, still Diamond Bar HQ under Samsung</li>
            <li><b>Modernist Column specialty</b> — panel-ready shim protocol, FreshZone diagnostics</li>
            <li><b>Samsung-shared parts chain</b> — Digital Inverter compressor platform, strong LA supply</li>
            <li><b>$89 residential diagnostic</b> — waived when you authorize the repair</li>
          </ul>
        </div></section>

  <BrandBranchesGrid />

  <section class="trust-bar">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span>BHGS #A49573 · Insured</span>
      <span>Same-day in 5 SoCal counties</span>
      <span>Residential diagnostic $89 · waived with repair</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Dacor in LA — a California brand hiding in plain sight</h2>
      <p>
        Dacor's LA story is older than most homeowners realize. Stanley M. Joseph started the business in Pasadena
        in 1965 as Distinctive Appliances Corporation — yes, that's where the name came from. His sons Michael and
        Anthony ran it through the second generation; the company stayed family-owned, California-based, and
        family-run for 51 years until Samsung Electronics acquired it in August 2016 for about $150 million. What a
        lot of LA owners don't know: the US operation is still local. Dacor's current headquarters is in Diamond Bar,
        roughly 30 miles east of our Los Angeles branch. Engineering, product management, sales, and leadership work
        from that California campus; Samsung provides the refrigeration platform and global distribution
        infrastructure. For our techs, this history matters in service calls: we've been opening Dacor refrigerators
        since before the Samsung deal closed, and the Samsung-era parts chain is particularly strong in LA precisely
        because Dacor is still run locally.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Dacor households we serve most regularly are the ones where a California custom builder or kitchen
        designer spec'd Dacor between 2008 and 2016 — a period when Dacor was the premium California-brand
        alternative to Sub-Zero and Thermador in new construction across Beverly Hills, Hollywood Hills, Pasadena
        hillside renovations, and Pacific Palisades. That pre-Samsung installed base is still running strong. Post-
        2016, the Modernist Column has become a genuine architect-spec call again, especially for clients who want
        luxury refrigeration at 10–20% below Sub-Zero pricing with a strong forward parts chain.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>Dacor refrigerator failures our techs see most often</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Pattern data from running Dacor service across LA. Six clusters cover the bulk of dispatch. On pre-2016
        Preference-series units the failure profile skews toward legacy electronics; on current Modernist Column and
        Contemporary French Door it skews toward sensor drift and integrated-install alignment.
      </p>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>FreshZone drawer symptom: meat freezing or produce wilting</h3>
        <p>
          Most-common Modernist Column call. Homeowner reports the FreshZone drawer is either too cold (meats
          freezing at the "chill" setting) or too warm (produce wilting at the "produce" setting). Root cause is
          almost always the FreshZone zone sensor drifting, or frost blocking the airflow baffle. Diagnostic order:
          read zone sensor through the Dacor service interface, verify against a calibrated probe, inspect baffle
          for frost, check the drawer-pan drain for blockage. Sensor replacement $180–$340; baffle defrost + verify
          $160–$260. The symptom looks serious; the fix is usually small.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Modernist Column panel drift — reveal gap widens after a year or two</h3>
        <p>
          Panel-ready Modernist Columns with heavy custom-hardwood cabinet panels: after 12–24 months the panel
          settles on one side, the reveal gap widens, and the flush plane shifts. Cause is usually hinge closer
          tension wasn't adjusted at install for the panel weight. Fix is hinge re-shim plus closer tension
          adjustment. Our techs carry the Dacor offset gauge and closer-spring kit; 90-minute job. When cabinet
          settling is the root cause (not hinge), that's contractor scope — we tell you which side the issue is on.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Digital Inverter compressor noise — long warranty, occasional early failure</h3>
        <p>
          Dacor's Samsung-era refrigerators use the Digital Inverter compressor platform shared with Samsung's
          premium line. Generally reliable with a 12-year parts warranty on the compressor specifically, but we do
          see occasional early bearing noise (audible humming that wasn't there when new) on units installed 2018–
          2020. If the noise is within factory coverage, we handle the warranty claim for the part; labor is the
          homeowner's cost after year 2. Post-warranty compressor swap $1,000–$1,800 depending on SKU and refrigerant.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Contemporary French Door ice-maker — LA hard-water pattern</h3>
        <p>
          Ice production drops progressively over 6–12 months on Contemporary French Door units in Encino, Sherman
          Oaks, Tarzana, Calabasas, Pasadena — LA's harder-water neighborhoods. Fill valve scales, flow drops, ice-
          mold fills partially. Descale the water path, inspect and possibly replace the fill valve, verify ice-maker
          module cycles. Standard descale + fill-valve service $280–$440. Annual descaling recommended for heavy-
          ice households in hard-water areas.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Pre-2016 Preference-series board faults — legacy platform consideration</h3>
        <p>
          Preference-series refrigerators from before the Samsung acquisition occasionally throw control-board
          faults as they age past 12 years. The pre-Samsung independent parts chain has aged out for certain board
          SKUs; our techs have sourcing relationships for most legacy Dacor electronics, but on the oldest units
          some specific boards are end-of-production and require aftermarket alternatives or secondary suppliers.
          We quote the specific replacement path before authorization so the legacy-platform premium is transparent.
          If the board fault is on a unit 15-plus years old and the replacement cost approaches 40–50% of a new
          unit, we walk through repair-vs-replace math honestly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Dacor vs. Samsung parts confusion — real versus rumored</h3>
        <p>
          One diagnostic trap worth naming. Current-generation Dacor and Samsung premium refrigerators share the
          Digital Inverter compressor platform, many sealed-system components, and parts of the electronics
          architecture — but they are NOT interchangeable units. Some online forums and occasionally less-experienced
          techs assume "Samsung part works in Dacor" or vice versa. Some components do cross; others have different
          firmware, different sensor calibration, or different mounting, and installing a Samsung-spec part in a
          Dacor can produce erratic behavior. Our techs source Dacor-spec parts through the Dacor aftermarket
          channel (which runs on the Samsung backbone but with Dacor-specific SKUs). If a prior tech installed a
          Samsung-cross part and the fridge is behaving erratically, we diagnose that as a known trap and correct
          the swap.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>Dacor US refrigerator lines we service</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        The Dacor residential refrigerator lineup spans current Modernist Column + Contemporary French Door plus the
        legacy Preference-series installed base. Wine columns (DWR) and undercounter units round out the scope.
      </p>
      <div class="model-grid">
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>Modernist Column 36" — DRR36980</h3>
          <p>Flagship column refrigerator. 36-inch width, integrated panel-ready, FreshZone climate drawer, Digital
          Inverter compressor, three-zone cooling. Installed in architect-spec kitchens as the California-local
          alternative to Sub-Zero 648PRO and Thermador Freedom.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>Modernist Column 30" — DRR30980</h3>
          <p>Narrower column variant. Same architecture as the 36, smaller footprint. Popular in Westside condo
          kitchens and pantry integrations where column-pair (30 + freezer column) is the install pattern. FreshZone
          drawer included.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>Contemporary French Door — DRZ / DRD series</h3>
          <p>Stainless or Bordeaux finish, exposed-hinge French Door layout with drawer-style freezer lower.
          Current-generation models run Samsung-shared Digital Inverter compressors and full Dacor diagnostic
          interface support. Common in post-2018 renovations across LA.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>DWR built-in wine columns</h3>
          <p>Dual-zone or single-zone wine columns, panel-ready integrated fronts. Often paired with Modernist
          Column refrigerators in entertaining-focused kitchens. Service profile adjacent to the refrigerator column
          — same diagnostic interface, same parts channel, narrower refrigeration architecture.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>Preference series (pre-2016) — installed base</h3>
          <p>Pre-Samsung Dacor refrigerators from 2005–2015. Still common in LA custom-build kitchens. Legacy
          electronics platform with some end-of-production board SKUs; refrigeration side generally serviceable with
          aftermarket or secondary-sourced parts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>Undercounter and under-cabinet built-ins</h3>
          <p>EF24 and under-counter refrigerator drawers. Installed in butler's pantries, wet bars, kitchen islands.
          Single-zone refrigeration, service profile simpler than the column platforms. Common install in Newport
          Coast and Palos Verdes entertaining spaces.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Dacor Modernist Column vs Sub-Zero vs Thermador — the LA-local column conversation</h2>
      <p>
        The three-way decision our clients describe most often on Modernist Column service calls: why did they pick
        Dacor over Sub-Zero or Thermador? We don't sell appliances, so the answer comes from what our techs have
        heard on dozens of service visits.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>Sub-Zero</b> is the US luxury default, Wisconsin-built, Bakke-family-owned since 1945, strongest LA parts
        supply chain. Factory parts same-day or next-day to Bel Air. Premium pricing — typically 15–25% above an
        equivalent Modernist Column for comparable spec. See <a href="/brands/sub-zero-refrigerator-repair/">Sub-Zero
        refrigerator repair</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>Thermador</b> is BSH's luxury column (Freedom Collection), shared BSH parts chain with Bosch. Strong
        flexibility in column-width combinations. See <a href="/brands/thermador-refrigerator-repair/">Thermador
        refrigerator repair</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>Dacor Modernist Column</b> slots in as the California-local value option: 10–20% below equivalent Sub-Zero,
        Samsung-era parts chain, FreshZone climate drawer signature, Diamond Bar HQ means the service network runs
        close to home. Often picked when the household wants true luxury refrigeration without the Sub-Zero premium,
        and likes the idea of supporting a California-brand legacy. The Samsung ownership doesn't seem to bother
        most LA clients once they understand the California HQ is still intact.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our team services all three equally. None is objectively better; they're differently positioned. For an LA
        homeowner deciding at the point of purchase: if parts availability on a 15-year horizon is the concern,
        Sub-Zero has the longest legacy track record. If sticker price matters and you want a strong forward-looking
        parts chain, Modernist Column is a genuine value pick.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>What Dacor refrigerator repair typically costs</h2>
      <p class="intro">Parts and labor vary between current Modernist/Contemporary (Samsung-era parts chain) and
      pre-2016 Preference-series (legacy platform). We quote the specific SKU before authorization.</p>
      <table class="price-table">
        <tr><th>Service</th><th>Typical Range</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Residential diagnostic</td><td>$89</td><td>Flat, waived if repair is authorized same visit</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Door gasket (Contemporary French Door)</td><td>$220 – $400</td><td>Standard stainless or Bordeaux finish</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Door gasket (Modernist Column)</td><td>$280 – $460</td><td>Panel-weight-adjusted shim + closer tension</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FreshZone sensor or baffle service</td><td>$180 – $360</td><td>Diagnosed via Dacor service interface</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Condenser fan motor replacement</td><td>$280 – $480</td><td>Common Modernist and Contemporary specs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Evaporator fan / defrost heater</td><td>$260 – $520</td><td>Defrost cycle faults and temperature drift</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Integrated-panel hinge re-shim</td><td>$240 – $420</td><td>Modernist Column specifically</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ice-maker fill valve + descaling</td><td>$280 – $440</td><td>Hard-water LA households</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Main control board replacement</td><td>$480 – $780</td><td>Higher on pre-2016 legacy boards</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Digital Inverter compressor (Samsung-era)</td><td>$1,000 – $1,800</td><td>Post-warranty labor after year 2</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DWR wine column evaporator service</td><td>$380 – $580</td><td>Zone-specific, parts via Dacor channel</td></tr>
      </table>
      <p class="small">
